{{About|the philosopher|the guitarist|Michael Hinton (guitarist)}}
'''John Michael Elliott Hinton''' (4 July 1923 – 3 February 2000<ref name=Gazette>{{cite web | title= Oxford University Gazette, 24 February 2000: Obituaries - Worcester College | url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/gazette/1999-00/weekly/240200/coll.htm#7Ref | accessdate=2008-04-07}}</ref>) was a British philosopher. He was a lecturer at the [[University of Oxford]] from 1958 and a fellow of [[Worcester College, Oxford]] from 1960.<ref name=Gazette /> He was Cowling Visiting Professor at [[Carleton College]] in 1978-79.<ref>{{cite web | title= Cowling Visiting Professors| url=http://apps.carleton.edu/curricular/philosophy/cowling/ |accessdate=2010-03-16}}</ref> He was previously a lecturer at [[Victoria University College]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Philosophy lecturer J.M. Hinton and Professor George Hughes | work=Victoria University of Wellington 1899 ~ 1999 A History | url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/BarVict-fig-BarVict268a.html | accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref>
Hinton is widely cited as the first modern proponent of the [[disjunctivism|disjunctive]] theory of perception.<ref>{{cite book | title = Disjunctivism: Contemporary Readings | author = Alex Byrne and Heather Logue }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Snowdon | first1 = Paul | title = The Objects of Perceptual Experience | journal = Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society, Supplementary Volumes | volume = 64 | pages = 121–166 | year = 1990 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> This view is set out in his 1973 book ''Experiences: An Inquiry Into Some Ambiguities'',<ref>{{cite book | title = Experiences: An Inquiry Into Some Ambiguities | author = John Michael Hinton | date = 1973 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=iLTUAAAACAAJ | accessdate = 2008-04-07 | publisher = Clarendon Press }}</ref> and in some papers dating as far back as 1966.
